{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17599474","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17599474"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T11:54:53+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T11:54:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15571"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15571","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15571"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.73,0.1,0.02,0.09,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8262"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"83504"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8262","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8262"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15571"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68377"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5103"},{"type":"tags","id":"5109"},{"type":"tags","id":"10053"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19959"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19962"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"83504","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/83504"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThyroid hormones play important roles in growth, development and metabolism throughout life, but are particularly crucial during fetal development.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following statements regarding thyroid physiology is correct?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Thyroid hormone is essential for neurodevelopment","Maternal hyperthyroidism typically results from iodine deficiency","Congenital hypothyroidism screening is no longer necessary","Low thyroid hormone levels increase gluconeogenesis","Thyroid hormones decrease cellular metabolic rate"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThyroid hormone is essential for neurodevelopment\u003C/strong\u003E, particularly during fetal life and early childhood. It plays a crucial role in neuronal migration, myelination, and synaptic development.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMaternal hyperthyroidism typically results from iodine deficiency\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect - iodine deficiency actually causes hypothyroidism since iodine is required for thyroid hormone synthesis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECongenital hypothyroidism screening is no longer necessary\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect - it remains a vital component of newborn screening programs worldwide as early treatment prevents intellectual disability and growth retardation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELow thyroid hormone levels increase gluconeogenesis\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect - thyroid hormones stimulate gluconeogenesis, so low levels would decrease this process.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThyroid hormones decrease cellular metabolic rate\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect - thyroid hormones increase cellular metabolism and oxygen consumption.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Thyroid hormone is critical for fetal brain development and neurodevelopment","Maternal iodine deficiency causes hypothyroidism, not hyperthyroidism","Congenital hypothyroidism screening is a vital part of newborn screening programs","Thyroid hormones increase gluconeogenesis and metabolism"],"references":["Brent GA. Mechanisms of thyroid hormone action. J Clin Invest. 2012 Sep;122(9):3035-43. doi: 10.1172/JCI60047. Epub 2012 Sep 4. PMID: 22945636; PMCID: PMC3433956","Melmed, S., Polonsky, K. S., Larsen, P. R., \u0026 Kronenberg, H. M. (2015). Williams textbook of endocrinology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Clark, O. H., Duh, Q. Y., Kebebew, E., Gosnell, J. E., \u0026 Shen, W. T. (Eds.). (2016). Textbook of endocrine surgery. JP Medical Ltd","Young, W. F. (2011). Netter\u0027s Endocrine System: Netter Collection of Medical Illustrations: Endocrine System E-book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Wass, J. A., \u0026 Stewart, P. M. (Eds.). (2011). Oxford textbook of endocrinology and diabetes. Oxford University Press. USA."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68377"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15571"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68377","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/68377"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-04T20:39:22+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-04T20:41:22+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8262"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"83504"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving info